text.desc: Capital letter 'A' represents the universal affirmative statement 'All S are P'.
text.title: A Statement: All S are P

text.desc: Capital letter 'I' represents the particular affirmative statement 'Some S are P'.
text.title: I Statement: Some S are P

text.desc: Capital letter 'E' represents the universal negative statement 'No S are P'.
text.title: E Statement: No S are P

text.desc: Capital letter 'O' represents the particular negative statement 'Some S are not P'.
text.title: O Statement: Some S are not P

g.desc: The Simplified Rule of Opposition (SRO) is an easy-to-remember (note the U-shape) and easy-to-use (see the algorithm below) logic tool that is functionally equivalent to the Traditional Square of Opposition (TSO). The basic layout of the SRO is similar to the TSO: the letters, A, E, I, O, representing the four categorical statements, are laid out as if each were at a corner of a square. Available for placement between the letters are either a single solid line or two dashed lines. The lines have the following meaning: 1. The statements at the ends of a solid line are true. 2. A statement at the end of a single dashed line is indeterminate. 3. A statement (either I or O) at the ends of two dashed lines is true. The algorithm for line placement is as follows: 1. Start with the SRO blank (i.e., with four letters but no lines). 2. Let a given statement be true or false. 3. Decide between which two letters to put the solid line. If (given its meaning) it can go in only one location, then that is where it goes and you are done. 4. If the solid line could go in more than one location, then put a dashed line in each of those locations and you are done.
g.title: Simplified Rule of Opposition

text.desc: The question mark indicates that the truth value for the A statement is unknown or indeterminate.
text.title: Unknown Truth Value for A Statement

path.desc: A solid vertical line between A and I indicates that both A and I are true.
path.title: Solid Vertical Line AI: A true; E false; I true; O false

rect.desc: If A is given as true, then the solid line must be placed between A and I. So, given the meaning of a solid line, A and I are both true. Because neither E nor O is at the end of any kind of line, each is false.
rect.title: Rectangle Around True

path.desc: The arrow indicates that E is false.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to False

path.desc: The arrow indicates that O is false.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to False

path.desc: The arrow indicates that I is true.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to True

path.desc: A solid vertical line between E and O indicates that both E and O are true while both A and I are false.
path.title: Solid Vertical Line EO: A false; E true; I false; O true

rect.desc: When E is given as true, the solid line must be placed between E and O. So, given the meaning of a solid line, E and O are both true. A and I are both false since neither is at the end of any kind of line.
rect.title: Rectangle Around True

path.desc: The arrow indicates that A is false.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to False

path.desc: The arrow indicates that I is false.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to False

path.desc: The arrow indicates that O is true.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to True

path.desc: A solid line between E and O indicates that both E and O are true while both A and I are false.
path.title: Solid Vertical Line EO: A false; E true; I false; O true

rect.desc: When I is given as false, then the solid line can only go between E and O. So, given the meaning of a solid line, E and O are both true. Since A and I are not at the end of any line, they are both false.
rect.title: Rectangle Around False

path.desc: The arrow indicates that E is true.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to True

path.desc: The arrow indicates that O is true.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to True

path.desc: The arrow indicates that A is false.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to False

path.desc: A solid vertical line between A and I indicates that A and I are true while E and O are false.
path.title: Solid Vertical Line AI: A true; E false; I true; O false

rect.desc: When O is given as false, the solid line can only be placed between A and I. So, given the meaning of a solid line, both A and I are true. E and O are both false because neither is at the end of any kind of line.
rect.title: Rectangle Around False

path.desc: The arrow indicates that A is true.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to True

path.desc: The arrow indicates that E is false.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to False

path.desc: The arrow indicates that I is true.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to True

path.desc: Dashed lines between E and O and between I and O indicate that O is true while E and I are both unknown.
path.title: Dashed Line EO

path.desc: Dashed lines between E and O and between I and O indicate that O is true while E and I are both unknown.
path.title: Dashed Line IO

rect.desc: If A is given as false, then the solid line can be placed either between E and O or between I and O. So two dashed lines should be placed in those locations. The result is that O is true because it is at the end of two dashed lines; E and I are both of unknown truth value because they are each at the end of a single dashed line; and A is false because it is not at the end of any line at all.
rect.title: Rectangle Around False

path.desc: The arrow indicates that the truth value of I is unknown.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to Question Mark

path.desc: The arrow indicates that the truth value of E is unknown.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to Question Mark

path.desc: The arrow indicates that O is true.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to True

path.desc: Dashed lines between AI and IO indicate that I is true while the truth values of A and O are unknown.
path.title: Dashed Line AI

path.desc: Dashed lines between AI and IO indicate that I is true while the truth values of A and O are unknown.
path.title: Dashed Line IO

rect.desc: When E is given as false, then the solid line could go either between AI or between IO. So it should be split into two dashed lines, one each going in those locations. The result is that I, at the end of two dashed lines, is true; A and O, each at the end of one dashed line, are both of unknown truth value; and E is false because it is at the end of no line at all.
rect.title: Rectangle Around False

path.desc: The arrow indicates that the truth value of A is unknown.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to Question Mark

path.desc: The arrow indicates that I is true.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to True

path.desc: The arrow indicates that the truth value of O is unknown.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to Question Mark

path.desc: Dashed lines between AI and IO indicate that I is true while the truth values of A and O are unknown.
path.title: Dashed Line AI

path.desc: Dashed lines between AI and IO indicate that I is true while the truth values of A and O are unknown.
path.title: Dashed Line IO

rect.desc: When I is given as true, then the solid line could go either between A and I or between I and O. So a dashed line is to be placed in both those locations, indicating that I is true while the truth values of A and O are unknown. E, not at the end of any line at all, is false.
rect.title: Rectangle Around True

path.desc: The arrow indicates that the truth value of A is unknown.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to Question Mark

path.desc: The arrow indicates that E is false.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to False

path.desc: The arrow indicates that the truth value of O is unknown.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to Question Mark

path.desc: Dashed Lines between EO and IO indicate that O is true and that E and I have unknown truth value.
path.title: Dashed Line EO

path.desc: Dashed Lines between EO and IO indicate that O is true and that E and I have unknown truth value.
path.title: Dashed Line IO

rect.desc: When O is given as true, then the solid line can go either between EO or IO. So a dashed line goes in both those locations. The result is that O is true because it is at the ends of two dashed lines; E and I are unknown because they are at the end of a single dashed line; and A is false because it is not at the end of any kind of line.
rect.title: Rectangle Around True

path.desc: The arrow indicates that A is false.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to False

path.desc: The arrow indicates that the truth value of I is unknown.
path.title: Arrow Pointing to Question Mark

path.desc: The arrow indicates that the truth value of E is unknown.
